AU.name: Bhuni Buhi
notes.gen: set a trap here because they were having procupine issues. Set a trap, caught and killed it. One of two Aus in whole village where they still plant corn because risk is too high everywhere else

AU.name: Kain
notes.gen: this is now mostly peas and apple trees. Parts of it are unused/used for hay.

AU.name: Palegadh
notes.gen: there are few fields here where maybe people skip a few years, esp if there are a lot of trees on their property.Ê

AU.name: Rajgadh
notes.gen: kodra losses are tolerable as the stalks make good fodder even if grains are lost

AU.name: Bhadiyanag
inactive.notes: this was a bit tricky. I think what's happening is that there's a part of it that's quite bad, but the owners will occaasionally plant there. The rest of it is hard ot protect,, so they just use it for peas and wheat.

AU.name: Gungudar
notes.gen: also some apple trees here

AU.name: Mathiyana
notes.gen: One of the few remaining Aus (along with Bhuni Buhi) where they still plant corn. Because corn is so difficult to protect, they're keeping it to the villages that are closest to the village with the hopes that the guards on the edges of the village will keep out the wildlife, and als because they are  easiest to monitor passively

AU.name: Shilang
notes.gen: Shilang, nashyantar: When a guard is hired, they monitor both. when they have a vilalge level montoring system, the person on duty here on a given day will also monitor nashyantar

AU.name: Nashyantar
notes.gen: Shilang, nashyantar: When a guard is hired, they monitor both. when they have a vilalge level montoring system, the person on duty here on a given day will also monitor nashyantar

AU.name: Kusmdin
notes.gen: Often have yearlong fallows

AU.name: Kusumdin old
notes.gen: The biggest problem here was rodents, not monkeys.

AU.name: Bada Phat
notes.gen: Water is limited here and therefore a problem some years. Despite being distant from the village, fairly well monitored becyase it's near a well-trafficked pasture.
inactive.notes: didn't plant here for a few years. This is typical. If they allow longer fallows, there's less eed for adding a lot of fertilizer/dung.

AU.name: Sonal
notes.gen: this is rather good land (good water so would be appropriate for vegetables), but tends to be underused. Even mustard is usually only planted every other year.
inactive.notes: regularly have 2-3 year fallows
notes.weather: mustard pest, destroyed about 40% of last crop

AU.name: Lippat
notes.gen: this is rather good land (good water so would be appropriate for vegetables), but tends to be underused. Even mustard is usually only planted every other year.
inactive.notes: regularly have 2-3 year fallows
notes.weather: mustard pest, destroyed about 40% of last crop

AU.name: Luchandin
notes.gen: Sant Ram. lives in the village. Planted peas here, but after many years of it being empty. Used MREGA funds for it to redeveloped, about 5 years ago, and has been used for peas since.Êdon't plant alu and wheat here. it's far away, and there's a high risk of monkeys. they have a permanent chaukidar when they have peas planted.

AU.name: Kallad
notes.gen: This one was a bit confusing to me as to why it's not farmed anymore. It's highly visible and apparently the soil is very good. Ramlal says the area is difficult for a few reasons. Always had a lot of tree cover.  It's visible from the village but takes some time to get to from the village, and people don't usually have reasons to jut walk by it.
inactive.notes: A part (about 15-20%) belongs o one person and is being used as an apple orchard

AU.name: Nayi Paddaar
notes.gen: Near the river and along the other edges bordering the forest, some of the families lost maybe upto 30% crops. For their monitoring, they wait until they see monkeys. When they do, they'll hold a meeting, and all go out together. Especially focus on areas marked out on mak as "monkey high". In this village, the bigger issue is procupines that come at night. they live under rocks and such, especially near small water modies. Giddad are a problem in corn. Crows are a problem for the corn. BUT, for none of these do they use any organized mechanism to get rid of them, the losses are quite low. they also come at night so not much you can do. even if overall they have a bigger impact, it's spread out more. when it's monkeys, they come in a big group and can do a lot of damage so it's worth it to organize to get rid of them.
notes.weather: hail, last year, more than 50%  fell over, but still salvagable

AU.name: Shkolang
notes.gen: the area near the road doesn't get too many monkeys, but the higher areas do. They also graze around here so it's easier to monitor.
notes.weather: hail, last year, more than 50%  fell over, but still salvagable

AU.name: Chaapak
notes.gen: No monkeys here! Or at least, very little. No issues with animals in genreal, maybe a bit of porcupine
notes.weather: hail, not much issues with pests

AU.name: Khachyaad
notes.gen: no monkeys here either. Not much animals in general. Low pests

AU.name: Thannersar
notes.gen: No issues with monkeys or other wildlife here either.

AU.name: Chibdikhaan
notes.gen: Monkeys are pretty bad. A major concern here is that the land is good for peas, but not great, and it's hard to protect.

AU.name: Shil
notes.gen: LOTS of monkeys here. Soil is very good though. This year, for the first time in about 15 years, one person has decided to have somebody else grow peas for them on this land. that person will also be in charge of protection. They will have their work cut out for them.

AU.name: Shilkutil
notes.gen: Lots of monkeys ehre as well. Also far from the village, so difficult to monitor.

AU.name: Riyaal
notes.gen: Lots of monkeys. If they didn't have monkeys it would be good land for peas. They only plant in the monsoon (rajma) because it can for the most part be passivly monitored. They probably only monitor here when they're grazing around there anyway.
notes.weather: Hail. No pests. This land used to be o, but it's right near the road and may have ended up with lots of rocks in it because of all the construction near by.

AU.name: Kathhyaan
notes.gen: They're plant some potatoes, but mostly for hosuehold consumption. Lost of monkeys, so rajma is good as it doesn't ned to be watched as much, but people who plant peas (maybe 1-2 hh each year) watch their own.
inactive.notes: This has two parts unused, I'm only including one here. It's been abandoned 6 years. The other part has been abandoned for over 20

AU.name: Kathhyaan old
notes.gen: not sure why abandoned but possibly because too much monkey pressure, has a lot of tree cover on and nearby this plot. They still plant it every few years, but only for peas because the monkey pressue is too high. If they needed to plant it with peas every year then the soil degrades. if they were to plant other things, the soil would improve, but nobody wantds to plant lower value rtops there.

AU.name: Bhyaal
notes.gen: not much monkey threat

AU.name: Khadakutla
notes.gen: Again, more monkeys here, but people plant things with that in mind. Ie. No corn

AU.name: Grammankutla
notes.gen: could be used for peas and potatoes but nobody wants to really spend time guarding here, so they mostly just do rajma and mustard

AU.name: Thaltukhod
notes.gen: Monkeys are not at all a problem here, BUT they did have a major pest outbreak a few years ago, and they had a problem with the garlic this year because the soil retains water really well.
notes.weather: hail. Potato pest was really bad 2 years ago.Everyone had to spray, saved the crop.

AU.name: Lhingan
notes.gen: this is terrific land, in genreal. No monkey threat, drainage is good, soil is fertile.
notes.weather: Hail was NOT hit by the potato pest

AU.name: Gadiyaada
notes.gen: Some monkeys here, but not so much that it can't be managed by just not planting crops like peas that are sensitive to them.

AU.name: Rakn
notes.gen: All this land belongs to just one person (Mahinder singh, not the dhaba guy). House is nearby. The part that was abandoned was likely because it was too much work to watch all of it.
inactive.notes: One part of it has been abandoned for more than a decade (see map, to the east)

AU.name: Gaabdin
notes.weather: hail, not much issues with pests

AU.name: Baasdar
notes.gen: Monkeys are a problem here, so a number of fields have been abandoned, but note completely. One family still farms.
inactive.notes: use the uncultivated part for taking animals to graze

AU.name: Janot
notes.gen: Someone is taking charge of planting part of it this year (from the village), and putting a small part of it (maybe about 5000Rs) towards the vilalge coffers in return for being allowed to plant there. Chaitru ram. Will do all the tilling, weeding, protection himself.

AU.name: Pulechabavale
notes.gen: MONKEYS ARE NOT BAD HERE. Just a few patches. After a lot of discussion - Dhamchyan west does not plant wheat anymore, just garlic. They get their wheat needs met from the depot. This year they're kind of regretting this. Winter crop is either mustard or garlic.

AU.name: Chaav
notes.gen: no monkeys here, easy to monitor from village.

AU.name: Khait
notes.gen: Monkeys are not a problem here

AU.name: Naalkewarle
notes.gen: monkeys are a problem, but only for households closest to the water. The village DOES NOT require all households to participate in monitoring, so only the households that are affected will band together to protect (just the potato crop and ripening corn). so, collective guarding for potato, but only 5 households participate
notes.weather: pests are bad here. Esp for potatoes if not removed early

AU.name: Shaktor
notes.gen: monkeys are a problem but as with naalkewarle only affected families use rotaitonal monitoring (only 7 households)
notes.weather: potato pest bad bc it holds water

AU.name: Lahdi Upar
notes.gen: monkeys are quite bad

AU.name: Lahdi
inactive.notes: 2-3 families used their land to plant apples in the past 2-3 years. One family may have planted corn on their land once in the past 5 years.

AU.name: Mathhyanakhod
notes.gen: Mathhyanakhod, Chhamtu, Ukhalsairi: all get monkeys, so they have a paid guard for potatoes and rotational monitors for corn.

AU.name: Ukhalsairi
notes.gen: Mathhyanakhod, Chhamtu, Ukhalsairi: all get monkeys, so they have a paid guard for potatoes and rotational monitors for corn. The last time they had a corn crop, they had a very bad monkey attack. two years ago they lost about 40% of their corn, mostly in a single early morning monkey raid. I was told nearly everyone lost at least 10%, most were more than this.

AU.name: Chhamtu
notes.gen: Mathhyanakhod, Chhamtu, Ukhalsairi: all get monkeys, so they have a paid guard for potatoes and rotational monitors for corn.

AU.name: Ramankutk
notes.gen: 2 brothers' families (shopkeeper bhatkuram), they live on the land.  Lots of monkeys, they watch in themselves, and this is fairly easy bc they have their stores right near their property.

AU.name: Shikar
notes.gen: (shikar and kawalpaddar). not currently planted. lots of monkeys. decided not worth the effort to have rotaional monitoring for the corn this time so leaving it empty.Êthe lst time they had potatoes, they had a chaukidhar. 40,000.
inactive.notes: this year, using only for potatoes. Possibly because they had really heavy pest losses (in mustard crop) ast year, and the monkeys are bad, so it's only feasible if they can have a guard.

AU.name: Kawarapaddar
notes.gen: (shikar and kawalpaddar). not currently planted. lots of monkeys. decided not worth the effort to have rotaional monitoring for the corn this time so leaving it empty.Êthe lst time they had potatoes, they had a chaukidhar. 40,000.
inactive.notes: this year, using only for potatoes. Possibly because they had really heavy pest losses (in mustard crop) ast year, and the monkeys are bad, so it's only feasible if they can have a guard.

AU.name: Roopak
notes.gen: were also badly effected by the mustard disease, along with Shikar and Kwalpaddar. They are leaving it fallow this summer and winter, then planing potatoes again next year.

AU.name: Kahdareeda
notes.gen: wildlife losses in corn, potatoes. Devdar and Kail tress on the property as well as ban.
notes.weather: not much in the last year

AU.name: Shil
notes.gen: wildlife not a problem, really easy to monitor here

AU.name: Dhangar
notes.gen: wildlife not a problem, really easy to monitor here

AU.name: Shord
notes.gen: wildlife not a problem, really easy to monitor here

AU.name: Bator2
notes.gen: Monkeys are a problem, though their biggest losses were to boar last year, over half of total crop damaged

AU.name: Upli Bhuyi
notes.gen: monkeys are bad, and get more boar than other parts of village
notes.weather: some issues with pests in the past

AU.name: Bator1
notes.weather: some issues with pests in the past

AU.name: Kumadda
notes.gen: Land adjacent to village, very easy to monitor, monkeyd usually don't get this close.

AU.name: Paddhar
notes.gen: Land adjacent to village, very easy to monitor, monkeyd usually don't get this close.

AU.name: Khol
notes.gen: Land adjacent to village, very easy to monitor, monkeyd usually don't get this close.

AU.name: Talang
notes.gen: this is very much on the guard route. So even though monkey threat is high, guarding along the road ot alog the periphery of this plot in general.

AU.name: Baand
notes.gen: high potential for monkey loss, but it very well protected (especially during corn season) because the guard sits on the edge of this AU.

AU.name: Chaunthda
notes.gen: high potential for monkey loss, but it very well protected (especially during corn season) because the guard sits on the edge of this AU.

AU.name: Ghartyal
notes.gen: Don't know how many of these households are mostly absent.

AU.name: Marung
notes.gen: becuase this AU is distant, with small per-HH area, the village decided not to spend money on protecting it (would have cost them another chaukidar to monitor this plus Kudsang, who was asking for more money bc there are so many monkeys). so nobody's planting. Instead, using it as "ghasni" -- the DO plow it, butdon't sow... they just let the grass the grow (they might weed out the "bad" grass and leave the good stuff.
inactive.notes: this is both good quality land (near river) and very high risk for monkeys and expensive to protect. So have just been used for hat the last few years

AU.name: Kudsang
notes.gen: This AU used ot be part of the same "beat" as Marung. No longer used for anything except grass.
inactive.notes: this is both good quality land (near river) and very high risk for monkeys and expensive to protect. So have just been used for hat the last few years

AU.name: Upper Saperu
notes.gen: There are some homes here, but they aren't very close to a pakka road. So some of the households have more than one house, including one that's in a more convenient locations. In genreal people are spending less effort farming here, both summer and winter, than they used to.
notes.weather: aveage 10% losses to weather each year for corn in the summer, closer to 5% losses in the winter.

AU.name: Pasture near Gaihr
notes.gen: this could have been abandoned well over 20 years ago, but it's definitely at least 20.

AU.name: Lahdu
notes.gen: "other" here is mainly porcupines
notes.weather: yes. Weather losses generally higher than wildlife losses, at least on year in the past five years lost 25% of corn to storms. In most years losses are lower.

AU.name: Saperu main
notes.gen: this year about 50% is being used, and that's about normal. About 15% is completely unused, and the other 35% is not abandoned but used less regularly. The uppermost part, near the kacha road, may be underused/mostly used as pasture because the land is quite slopey and soil isn't very good. which most of the fields are visible from homes and some footpaths, there are a lot of trees here which cuts down on visibility.
inactive.notes: It seems like the majority of the area that's used for just hay is on the uppermost part of the AU, but there may be some other fields that are scattered around that are also mostly unused
notes.weather: lose corn to water issues, and what to hail. For both of these, losss are propbably around 5-7% per year.

AU.name: Lhingni
notes.gen: this is one of two Aus in Saperu that are irrigated and grow rice. In many ways this is functionally an extension of the rice-growing area of racchiara.
inactive.notes: a chunk of this land belongs to a single family that doesn't cultivate anymore, but they've handed it over to others who manage it for hay.
notes.weather: about 15% loss of rice to water-related issues, about 10% for wheat.

AU.name: Bhalvaat
notes.gen: see comments for lingni.
notes.weather: about 15% loss of rice to water-related issues, about 10% for wheat.

AU.name: Upper Rachhiara
notes.gen: High development area, a lot of formerlly ag (but low quality) land converted to single homes.
inactive.notes: the upper part of this AU has been mostly used for development or in genreal not used for ag. This are was largely owned by SC families, and was marginal, and therefore fairly cheap when outsiders were looking for areas to develop.

AU.name: Upper Rachhiara on road to Nanahar
notes.gen: Still in use, but not as much as previously, especially on the side above the road.
inactive.notes: about 60% still in use, the upper part (above the road) is largely unused with the exception of one guy's lot, that is fenced.

AU.name: Upper Rachhiara main settlement
inactive.notes: central part is unused. Looks like probably because it's lower quality soil. Used for grazing

AU.name: Rachhiara near stores
notes.gen: Not much wildlife loss here, partly because it's near a well trafficed area and also near homes. About 10% of this area is homegardens, which are fenced.
notes.weather: 5% losses winter and summer due to weather

AU.name: Above Ghoda
notes.gen: this is probably the best land in the village. Had the healthiest looking corn. Not used at all for fodder. Makes sense as it's irrigated, and also very close to homes. There is a road running along two of its sides, and the houses along the northern edge seems quite nice. I suspect this is a wealthier part of the village.
notes.weather: no major issues in general, but 4 years ago had a lot of issues with hail that destroyed fruit flowers, and excess rain was a problem for the corn. In general losses are under 5pc

AU.name: Near Kandbari Nala
notes.gen: the middle part used to be a small tea plantation that's now unused and fairly overgrown. The lower part is also not heavily used. The upper part is still used and partly irrigated.

AU.name: Ghoda
notes.gen: this is where madhu lives. About 10% of this area was used for potatoes in winter. for two households,all of it got dug up by boar soon after it was planted. they were able to plant again. These fields were right up against the houses.

AU.name: Lahdi
notes.gen: All but one of the families owning land here live in Ghoda. One family has a house here which they live in for part of the year.

AU.name: Rachhiara main
notes.gen: households from saperu, rachhiara, gahir, gorat, (ie, whole panchayat) have land here. as well as 4-5 families from bandla, who have built a house right in the middle of it where they bring all their animals. They're here form the wheat cutting, and all the rice work. so they spend about 2 months of the year here.  irrigated, really good land. Êrice is expensive and difficult bc few bulls, it's not as good with tractors, lots of work to transplant, etc. wheat is a bit easier so more of the area is planted during the winter. 5-10 years ago, you would have seen a ot more rice. now, many plots are used for cutting hay. it's still kept "clean", so there aren't too many places that are overgrown, weedy, or scrubby yet.

AU.name: Rachhiara Hay
notes.gen: this is right above the road from the little pine forest. This area is fenced, from what I can tell because it's used just as pasture now, though it's terraced and used to be used for ag. There are lots of fodder trees on it.
inactive.notes: also has lots of fodder trees

AU.name: Lower Rachhiara
notes.gen: Same as racchiara main, families from all over have land here. Again less planting as people get jobs. It's also become more expensive to farm since now everyone needs to buy inputs (fertilizer, pesticides) than there used to be when they used native seeds, and more dung (but... native seeds were less productive, at least compared to early years of HYVs, and dung is hard to carry and requires managing a lot more animals, for which there is also less time). No families lost more than 50%.

AU.name: Old rice fields
notes.gen:
Previously used for rice in monsoon. Seasonal stream nearby was used to flood the fields. Supposedly the water source is still available, but it's no longer used becyase of high wildlife pressure. Land is not suitable for corn, and less suitable than lower parts for wheat. 
One person (who owns the land but no longer lives in the village, is a dr somewhere) is attempting to plow it this year, but no plans to protect. Locals expect no real chance anything will survive.
inactive.notes: Used for grazing now. There is one small patch that's heavily fenced, owned by one guy who tries really hard to grow there. Rest is untilled

AU.name: Upper Suan top
notes.gen:
All of these fields had wheat in the previous season, but around 80% lost to wildlife. The season before, lost about 50% of corn to wildlife.
It is well fenced on the south side by a combo bamboo + living fence (mulberry) about 6 feet high. 
Roughly 7 families. 
Mostly watch themselves. Most fields are also fenced individually, or a few fields together. Quality of fence varies, thorugh wuite high and strong on the top (north) side. sometimes coalitions form for a few years, and they monitor together, then fall apart for various reasons, but usually becuase someone decides it's just not worth it for them anymore after multiple years of heavy losses.
inactive.notes: A number (about half?) of these families are currently planting a mix of corn and grass. As in, intentionally sowing both together. As best as I can tell, they cut the grass when it's reasonably long to use as feed. I got some complicated explanations of why they do this, but the ebst answer I got was that planting with grass is a bit of a deterrent to sambar and nilgai when the ears just start to appear. They have a preference for fields that are just corn. If htey do this, the other advantage is having more good quality feed. on the flipside, it produces less corn.
notes.weather: hail this past spring. Estimated 5-10% losses to wheat on average

AU.name: Upper Suan Sukhram
notes.gen:
Belongs to sukhram and fam (techniacally 4 households, but closely related). Pretty much the best protected land in the village. heavy fencing, plus monitoring (1st party rotational) for both winter wheat and monsoon corn. 
last season, lost about 20% of wheat, mainly to sambar and nilgai. 
Previous season, lsot of 15% of corn, about 10% to boar and 5% to other things but mostly birds. 
The "system" they have for protecting is a bit vague, but definitely qualifies at rotational. they just make sure that someone from the large joint family is out there during sensitive parts of the season (when the wheat is a few inches tall, when ears start appearing on the corn). they do tend to take turns. If they ahve an attack one night, there is a more concerted effort following that. It may be one person, or it may be a few together.
inactive.notes: If my data is correct only half of this was used for wheat, but all of it was planted with corn/hay
notes.weather: hail this past spring. Estimated 5-10% losses to wheat on average

AU.name: Upper Suan central
notes.gen: somewhat well protected with some fences, but overall people here seem to be relying on the fact that much of this is close to, or somehwat visible from the village.
notes.weather: hail this past spring. Estimated 5-10% losses to wheat on average

AU.name: Upper Suan near river
notes.gen: overgrown with weeds, not used for grazing or grass. Based on google earth imagery it looks like it was in use as recently as 2011.
inactive.notes: I think there may be a few small homegardens in here, but otherwise abandoned. Now quite overgrown with shrub
notes.weather: hail this past spring. Estimated 5-10% losses to wheat on average

AU.name: Lower Suan central
notes.gen: these are NOT fenced, so unlike in upper suan, they're much more succeptible to stray cattle. I was told ungulates are a much bigger problem than stray cattle since in theory they had them rounded up recently, but I suspect the ungulate %age is an overestimate and the cattle %age is an underestimate. also, possibly a reduction in boar threat compared to ungulates becuase of hunting
inactive.notes: the last time the majority of this area was planted was 2 years ago. Most of the owners got together, fenced the area. Still lost most of their crop (I believe this was the winter so it would have been wheat). This past year, about 4 families sowed part of their land holdings for a total of 10% of the total area. Nearly all of it was lost, mostly to ungulates and stray cattle, maybe 5% to weather related problems.
notes.weather: hail this past spring. Estimated 5-10% losses to wheat on average

AU.name: Lower Suan middle
inactive.notes: this bit is a mix of cut grass, growing grass, a few burned fields, and a few wthat are low-density weeds which look like they were managed by haven't been yet this season.
notes.weather: hail this past spring. Estimated 5-10% losses to wheat on average

AU.name: Lower Suan bottom
inactive.notes: This is mostly covered in low weeds now, with a lot of scrub and lantana alont the western edge. Looks like it was kept cut until fairly recently (silimar to Lower suan Middle) but is now a lot weedier looking.

AU.name: Laad main
notes.gen: The people who own land in this AU have entered an agreement with the ag dept (at the block level) for a solar powered electric fence (which they call the "solar fence" locally). Owners have agreed to pay 20% of the cost, the government will pay the rest. The government will hire the labor and do the installation, and I think also the maintainance (for additional costs?). They hope to start work on this after the monsoon. In the meatime, most of this area is fenced with bamboo and branches, though it's not fully enclosed; some parts are open. When I visited the Pradhan pointed out where a sambar or two (he thinks) had walked through the fields that had been prepared for transplanting rice.
notes.weather: yes. Last year was uncommonly bad. Lost about 50% to weather issues. Most years it's more like 10% losses.

AU.name: Laad lower
notes.gen: I didn't get to look at this area closely, but saw a bit of it from the suan side. There's a bit of cultivation still goin on, but I think much of it has been unused for about 10 years.
inactive.notes: near the river, but also a reasoably accessible part of the village. Just some of the plots are still farmed though.

AU.name: Laad mini
notes.gen: this is more or less contiguous with Laad main, but cut off by the road. Didn't get to take a look but was told it's a combo of homegardens (fenced) and larger fields.

AU.name: Mandbasti Upper 1
notes.gen: did not spend much time here. On follow-up phone call, was told that they have some minimal shared protection, mostly in the form of making sure someone is going out at night to beat drums and make a racket to hopefully deter animals. This happens in Upper Masandbasti 1, 2, and Lohakkar central.

AU.name: Mandbasti Upper 2
notes.gen: did not spend much time here. On follow-up phone call, was told that they have some minimal shared protection, mostly in the form of making sure someone is going out at night to beat drums and make a racket to hopefully deter animals. This happens in Upper Masandbasti 1, 2, and Lohakkar central.

AU.name: Masandbasti Top
notes.gen: pradhan's land. he's the only one growning. Has some fences up, but not very strong ones. For the summer, set up a platform so that at least some of the fields coul be watched more closely at night by someone he's hired to keep watch. Also has a pulley contraption that allows the watchman to make constant noise. becuase the plots that are farmed here are disjointed (becuase of the way the land was split up between four brothers), and the others are not interested in using the land, there isn't much scope for more efficient protection.
inactive.notes: pradhan's land, along with a few other families. All keep fields free of weeds, but most are not planting anything.

AU.name: Mandbasti Lower 1
notes.gen: now covered in trees, oritinal terracing still visible. Some lantana, but it's somewhat under control as this area is still used a bit for hay and fodder.
inactive.notes: overgrown, basically forest now

AU.name: Mandbasti Lower 2
notes.gen: now covered in trees, oritinal terracing still visible. Some lantana, but it's somewhat under control as this area is still used a bit for hay and fodder.
inactive.notes: overgrown, basically forest now

AU.name: Masandbasti lumber
notes.gen: not in use for at least 10 years, but still productive as it's actively being managed for lumber (on a fairly small scaleÉ. Ie not a ton of trees, but enough for the owner (pradhan, again) to make a small profit).
inactive.notes: pradhan sells wood from land for lumber

AU.name: Lohakkar Kola Central
notes.gen: Take turns using noise to deter wildlife during crucial parts of corn season, and if it seems necessary during the wheat season.
inactive.notes: just used for cutting grass

AU.name: Lohakkar Kola below road
notes.gen: this area is really only homegardens, and I'm not sure if I should include it as being separate from the rest of Lower Lohakkar, but doing so for now.
inactive.notes: about 10% in use for homegardens. rest unused for about 10 years. 4 families. Seem like some of the wealthier folks in town.

AU.name: Lohakkar Kola Lower
inactive.notes: overgrown, basically forest now
